	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>HAND OF THE HAMMERS, PART III</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><p>Boy parts and girl parts are different.</p>

<p>Khaleb noticed this as Ursi peeled off her leathers to wade into the hot spring. The years of hunting together, of camping on the tundra each night, had made nudity a non-issue, and by now he could recite every scar and birthmark on her form from memory. At first, this had hardly mattered. Youth, after all, made nearly everyone genderless in the eyes of one another.</p>

<p>But now those scars and birthmarks rested over the swell of budding breasts, in the curve of a dipping waist, on the plains of a flat stomach. And Khaleb’s quick eyes drank it all in with a new appreciation. His own body had started changing, bulking up and fleshing out in new and different ways. He had endured no end of teasing about his crackling voice from the shaman he traveled with.</p>

<p>Boy parts and girl parts are different. This, indeed, was a good and right thing.</p>

<p>“…leave the tundra soon. I was thinking we should try our luck in the Karanas. There should be plenty of prey, and I hear there are bandits we can cut down – Khaleb, are you listening to me?”</p>

<p>“Hmm?” Admittedly, he had missed half of what she was saying. It seemed to have gotten lost somewhere in that ripening valley. “You’re probably right, Ursi. We need to branch out.”</p>

<p>She raised an eyebrow. “What are you staring at?”</p>

<p>“I’m not staring. I wasn’t looking at anything in particular, really. Just letting my mind wander…” …where I might like my hands to, he finished mentally.</p>

<p>“Let them wander somewhere else.” She snorted, then allowed her eyes to drift over him. The warriors in the taverns at night did not stand much taller, but their bodies carried a mass that Khaleb couldn’t touch. Theirs spoke of heavy plate and large weapons. His whispered of light, quiet leather and small, fast weapons. In the privacy of her thoughts, she pondered exploring the differences between boy and girl, between warrior and rogue.</p>

<p>But this was Khaleb. Her annoyance. Her friend. Her brother. Her…he was doing it again. Self-consciousness welled, and she sunk her nude self neck deep in the warm water. “Khaleb, stop staring!”</p>

<p>He slid into the water next to her. “I’m not staring, Ursi.” Her lips were very close. He could smell her, and the scents were all heady, new. Water glistened over her skin, silver in the moonlight, and the steam from the hot springs stuck her russet hair to her face in very appealing curls. Moving smoothly through the springs, he placed his face strategically in front of hers. “I’m not staring. I am simply…appreciating.”</p>

<p>She shifted backwards. “Have you been drinking? Did the orc hit you on the head?”</p>

<p>He edged forward again. Breathing her name, he softly puckered his lips, and his eyes slid closed. His hand slowly moved towards her, seeking her skin as his lips sought hers. A trickle of sweat ran behind his ear just as both hand and lip found their targets.</p>

<p>Pain exploded in his left cheek as the crack of Ursi’s hand rang through the night. The noise startled several snow rabbits nearby, but not nearly so badly as the barrage of insults and profanity that came next. As he sat blinking, staring off into the darkness, he pondered the legitimacy of her statements. He was fairly certain that his parents had been married, but since he had never met them, he could hardly prove that his mother had been an orc and his father some sort of small farm animal.</p>

<p>She pulled herself from the springs, wrapping herself hastily in her towel and continuing to call curses down on him. He gingerly touched the throbbing red mark on his face. He didn’t think that his aunt had been overly friendly with the goblins, and certainly not for pay, but Ursi seemed awfully vehement about it.</p>

<p>Some parts of Ursi may have changed, but her hand was still the same. And so, it seemed, was her temper. He sighed. It was going to be a long week.</p> </font></td>
	</tr>
